Nvidia Earnings
---------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/business/earnings/nvidia=
-nvda-q2-earnings-report-2025-16fc82a2 ) :

Nvidia=E2=80=99s sales and earnings more than doubled in the company=E2=80=
=99s most recent quarter, showcasing the momentum of the nearly two-year-ol=
d AI boom despite concern that investment has surged ahead too quickly. The=
 company also said Wednesday that gross profit margins narrowed in the quar=
ter compared with the period that ended in April. Chief Financial Officer C=
olette Kress pinned the blame partly on production issues with Nvidia=E2=80=
=99s next-generation Blackwell chips that required a design tweak. The comp=
any, however, said that production will ramp up as expected and that demand=
 is strong.

The overall results, while still robust, highlighted challenges from the in=
creased complexity of Nvidia=E2=80=99s newest products, and showed its grow=
th slowing from the supercharged clip over the past year. Investors respond=
ed by sending the company=E2=80=99s shares down more than 6% in after-hours=
 trading. Through Wednesday=E2=80=99s close, the shares had gained more tha=
n 150% this year alone, pushing Nvidia=E2=80=99s valuation above $3 trillio=
n and making it the second-largest listed company in the world, behind Appl=
e.

Nvidia=E2=80=99s results seemed fine, particularly if you thought through t=
he implications of the Blackwell delay; speaking of O=E2=80=99Laughlin, he =
wrote before the earnings call on Fabricated Knowledge ( https://www.fabric=
atedknowledge.com/p/earnings-preview-nvidia-and-marvell/ ) :

I believe the story will be about the GB200 and B100 delays. We already kno=
w this is happening. Dylan Patel and the SemiAnalysis team wrote about it i=
n depth, and we know margins will be meaningfully worse ( https://www.semia=
nalysis.com/p/nvidia-b100-b200-gb200-cogs-pricing ). We also understand tha=
t the GB200 is delayed ( https://www.semianalysis.com/p/nvidias-blackwell-r=
eworked-shipment ). Think with me right now. A considerable product delay h=
as been announced, the product is highly complicated, and the market has wh=
olly shrugged it off. There are so many ways that this could surprise the d=
ownside, and most delays aren=E2=80=99t free.

I think the delay is going to cost Nvidia a lot. Initially, they guided the=
 quarter to a low 70s gross margin, driven by a gradual shift to lower marg=
in B100s. That implies that even with a much lower amount of B100s (now can=
celed), the margins were in the 60s. The worst possible thing has happened:=
 We won=E2=80=99t see revenue, and ramp costs will still be there.

Margins, on the other hand, look almost delusional from the street. Dylan=
=E2=80=99s work above says that the BOM is twice as much, the ASP is only u=
p 40%-50% on the B100, and the GB200 is likely at least as bad in margins, =
if not worse. Estimates for gross margins next year are at ~75%, and that=
=E2=80=99s way too high. Nvidia has to address this, and this could be the =
quarter. I believe a 70% gross margin feels appropriate.

Nvidia=E2=80=99s margin came in higher than expected, as did its margin for=
ecast for next quarter; that makes O=E2=80=99Laughlin=E2=80=99s case about =
B100 margins, though, because shipping fewer than expected chips means that=
 revenue is dominated by higher-margin products. I do agree with O=E2=80=99=
Laughlin that that should be fine in the long run: Blackwell should be a hi=
ghly-differentiated product even relative to Hopper, given it is really the=
 first chip to be designed in a post-ChatGPT world, and margins will go up =
over time.

